    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1926-12-16T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1926-12-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="205"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d205">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">812.24/477</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Mexican Ambassador</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Téllez</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1926-12-16">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 16, 1926</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Excellency</hi>: With further relation to Your Embassy’s
                    note of October 15, 1926, in which it was stated that your Government was
                    negotiating with the Douglas Company of Los Angeles, California, for the
                    purchase of eight aeroplanes of the type used by the United States army,
                    together with equipment for bombardment, photography, electrical installation,
                    et cetera, I now have the honor to acknowledge the receipt of Your Excellency’s
                    note of November 30,<note n="61" xml:id="d205fn61">Not printed.</note> in which
                    you ask that I bring my influence to bear on the proper authorities to the end
                    that the Collector of Customs at Nogales, Arizona, be instructed to allow the
                    said aeroplanes, together with their equipment, to be exported to Mexico.</p>
                <p>I regret to have to inform Your Excellency that the competent authorities of this
                    Government have decided that it is not expedient under the present circumstances
                    to permit the exportation of these aeroplanes and their equipment to Mexico.</p>
                <p>Furthermore, I may say, that the general question of the maintenance of the arms
                    embargo is at this time being reconsidered by my Government.</p>
                <p>Accept [ect.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Frank B. Kellogg</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
